76561198113317431,Recommended,410340,30170832,Posted: 25 February,all,graham69parkinson,"Being fairly new to RC Drones I decided to get a few different simulators like this one, both FPV Freerider sims, Velocidrone, FPV Event and the free DRL Simulator. From the testing I've done there seems to be a large void between how each one feels and how close to the real thing they get, for example Liftoff seems to be more like an arcade game with the feeling I get from the controls, where it seems to have way to much punch the second you move the throttle stick. So just getting used to it isn't easy even when you fly in level/stability mode, it does get better in acro but the same issue with the punch power is still there. Like I've said I have several of these sims and the two I have found closest to real life are FPV Event and Velocidrone and it's because they both seem to be setup with real world physics. I fly a Robocat 270 racing drone and it has plenty of power and is capable of around 60/70 mph, and it feels nothing like the drones in Liftoff because they just shoot upwards like their on steroids.  And when it comes to the workbench screen I find the lack of contrast ridiculas because its hard to see whats on the screen unless im sat inches away from it, so I think the developers could take a look at changing the Font size and background colour to make it easier for people to be able to read the information either in the workbench parts description or the flight controller settings screen. Apaert from that I do think Liftoff has loads of scope to be improved and it will only take some tiny tweaks to get it close to a full on drone simulator, and at it's price point I do think it could be a whole lot better.  But if like me you are finding it hard to get your head around I would recommend trying some of the free ones like DRL simulator or the free trial of FPV Event, as like me you will notice just what I have, Liftoff is a great simulator but it's not quite real enough."
